Kepler measures rotation rate of stars in the pillar of the Pleiades
The latest mission with the Kepler Space Telescope has helped astronomers collect the most complete catalog of rotation rates among the stars of the Pleiades' star cluster.
The new data help astronomers to understand why stars rotate in the star cluster at different rates and in what connection the rotation periods with the planet formation are.
"We hope that by comparing our results to other star clusters, we learn more about the relationship between the mass of a star, its age, and even the history of its solar system," Luisa Rebull, a researcher at Caltech's Infrared Processing and Analysis Center in Pasadena, said in a press release.
The star cluster of the Pleiades is 445 light-years from Earth.
Many stars in this cluster of stars, which formed around 125 million years ago, now reach adulthood.
They are now spinning the fastest.
These ripening stars emit large amounts of stellar winds at peak rotation rates.
Since these winds travel through the magnetic fields of the stars, they have a braking effect on the stars.
As a star ages, its rotation rate begins to slow down.
Kepler measures the rotation rate of each star by recognizing the time between the appearance of a recognizable star spot -- like sunspots.
The latest catalog of rotation rates indicates that more massive stars rotate more slowly than fewer massive stars.
Rebull compares the stars to dancers, with larger stars spinning more slowly pirouettes than smaller ones.
"In the "ballet" of the Pleiades, we see that slow rotors tend to be more massive, whereas faster rotors tend to be very bright stars," Rebull said.
Since the star cluster of the Pleiades is so close, it serves as the ideal cosmic laboratory to compare stellar qualities such as rotation rates.
"The Pleiads' star cluster provides an anchor for theoretical models of stellar rotation in both directions, younger and older," Rebull said.
There is still a lot ahead of us about which we would like to learn more about how, when and why stars slow down their rotation rates and, so to speak, hang their "dance shoes".
Rebull and her colleagues have reported in detail in three newspaper reports on their latest analysis of the rotation rates of the Pleiades, which will soon be published in the Astronomical Journal.
