Data theft: So perfidious hackers extort their ransom
Programmers of blackmail malware are currently targeting companies - and are successful in doing so.
According to a recent survey by malware defense specialists Malwarebytes among 540 companies in North America, the United Kingdom and Germany, 40 percent of the companies surveyed have been victims of an attack with blackmail software at least once in the past twelve months, some of them several times.
In Germany, almost 20 percent of the companies were already once the target of ransomware blackmail.
40 percent of the victims willingly paid the ransoms demanded by the perpetrators in order to be able to use the attacked systems and data again.
The perpetrators are specializing their blackmail software, according to the observations of malware bytes, on attacks in corporate networks.
If they are successful there, the potentially extortionable ransom is significantly higher than for private users.
"We are currently observing a frighteningly rapid evolution of malware," explains Malwarebytes CEO Marcin Kleczynski in an interview with Welt.
In 2008, most malware programs were still designed to send out advertising.
Then the perpetrators discovered extortion software for themselves.
First, private users were the target, but the switch to company attacks took place in recent months frighteningly fast.
Ransomware works according to a simple pattern: Once active on a victim's computer, she specifically searches for recently changed files such as Word, Excel or database files, as well as archives of images and videos.
These files encrypt the ransomware and delete the originals sustainably.
The software then presents the requirements of the blackmailers.
In order to get the end key code to the files, the victims have to transfer money - usually in the form of the crypto currency Bitcoin.
But where the personal photo database is at stake for private users, companies are concerned with sensitive customer data or project databases, without which production is at a standstill.
Accordingly, the damage is higher when a ransomware strikes.
22 percent of the affected German companies reported loss of revenue due to ransomware, 13 percent even had to completely interrupt the business activity, in one case people were in danger of life.
In Germany, hospitals have been victims of attacks several times, whose patients can be acutely threatened by the loss of medical records.
"We always tell the victims: Do not pay, you only promote the problem," explains Kleczynski.
Yet 80 to 90 percent of companies that pay get their data back.
It is difficult for managers to reject the demand of the perpetrators in view of a standstill in the company.
The hackers, in turn, know this and are trying everything to build a good reputation.
In a recent study, F-Secure’s security researchers examined the user interfaces and contact with the blackmailers and come to the conclusion: The perpetrators are actually trying to build up a kind of customer service to take more money.
They explain to their victims via chat how they can pay via Bitcoin, set up freely accessible support websites or decrypt sample files for free.
And if private individuals are redeemed after payments of a few hundred euros, companies sometimes have to negotiate hard and pay five-figure sums to get their data back unencrypted.
Given the potentially high and relatively risk-free profits from ransomware blackmail, the hackers are becoming more and more professional and share the work, explains security expert Chester Wisniewski of antivirus provider Sophos: "A single person can write a ransomware about a week."
However, it is more likely that it is three or four people.
The programmers then sell their malware in the form of a software kit to the actual blackmailers.
The previous malware kits were created by buying the malware itself, consulting and additional tools for a one-time, fixed price between 1000 and 10,000 dollars.
"The scope of delivery includes an adjustment tool, so that smaller configurations, appearance and branding can be changed," says Wisniewski.
The blackmailers then look for more hackers to spread the freshly purchased software among the victims.
We live in a service economy.
So you log into one of the forums underground, buy the set from a criminal and instruct another to install the software on as many PCs as possible.
Payment is made per infected computer.
"Usually, the criminals then commission spammers to spread," Wisniewski explains.
The risk of ransomware is now known to many companies that better back up their data.
More than 50 percent of the company IT managers in the Malwarebytes survey trust to be able to defend ransomware using file back-ups and scanner software.
Accordingly, the perpetrators are already pursuing new strategies.
"If the encryption of data alone is no longer a sufficient threat to successful shooting, the perpetrators threaten to publish sensitive data such as customer lists or price calculations," explains Malwarebytes CEO Marcin Kleczynski.
Thus, the potential for damage is still many times higher than before, depending on the nature of the data.
In the future, the perpetrators could also target completely new goals in the Internet of Things.
At the Defcon hacker conference, security researchers demonstrated how they could get a thermostat connected to the Internet under their control.
In the middle of winter, the activation of such a blocked heater could well be worth a ransom to many victims.
If the perpetrators then block an entire production line in a factory instead of the heating in the future, ransomware could also become an issue in Industry 4.0.
