Relaxing Night: Tips for Sleep Disorders
In the evening you wall around forever, at night you lie awake for hours, in the morning you can no longer think of sleep far before the alarm clock ringing.
This is anything but relaxing.
After all, one is in good company with such problems: according to the Robert Koch Institute, about a quarter of adults have sleep disorders and more than ten percent perceive their sleep frequently or permanently as unrestful.
How do sleep problems or sleep disorders manifest themselves?
There are several forms of sleep disorders, and they can be based on a variety of causes, emphasizes Hans-Günter Weeß, a board member of the German Society for Sleep Research and Sleep Medicine.
What is commonly understood by this, however, is insomnia, i.e. a sleep-in and through-sleep disorder.
Especially sleeping through, many people find it unsatisfactory or inadequate, says Jens Wagenknecht, a board member of the German GPs Association with practice in Varel, Lower Saxony.
What is behind sleep disorders?
The causes of sleep disorders are complex.
Behind it can be organic, psychological or behavioral factors, but also drugs.
Not infrequently, the sleep disorder is an expression of another disease.
"Very early waking up is common, especially in the case of depression," says Weeß.
And it may be that different factors depend on each other.
For example, if you have a herniated disc, you can lie badly, wake up every two to three hours and possibly start to ponder everyday problems and worries, Weeß gives an example.
This leads to tension, and sleep is no longer possible.
When should you go to the doctor with sleep disorders?
Those who do not sleep well for a period of one month in at least three nights a week and are impaired in the day should go to the doctor, Weeß advises.
The impairment can look very different: you are knocked off, tired, unsleeped, have difficulties with attention and concentration, are easily irritable, have mood swings or physical complaints such as stomach or headaches.
To relieve the sleep disorder, it is important to find out their causes.
Treatment options include behavioral changes, cognitive behavioral therapy or medications - classic sleeping pills only in exceptional cases and at most for two weeks.
There are hardly any resident sleep doctors in Germany, emphasizes Prof. Ingo Fietze, head of the interdisciplinary sleep medicine center of Charité Universitätsmedizin Berlin.
Therefore, you should first contact the family doctor in case of sleep problems, advises Weeß.
