It doesn't sound like a neighborhood that majority wanted police protection from vandal leftists.
The ditch that the Berlin interior senator and the police open between squatters and their neighbors apparently does not exist.
Friedrichshain in the east of Berlin was actually a traditional working-class district, which still has a low average income and high risk of poverty compared to the rest of the city.
Occupations and the resulting housing projects have also been part of the neighbourhood for a long time: in 1990, numerous houses in the former GDR were occupied, including almost the entire Mainzer Straße very close to the Rigas.
While the Mainzers had been cleared in a real street battle under a large police force, many of the projects in the Riga were legalized and are still inhabited by the people who had occupied them 26 years ago.
At the same time, the district has increasingly become a magnet for tourists and Berlin voters from all over the world in recent years: residents from GDR times and former squatters now share their neighbourhood with them.
This is also reflected in the rents, which have risen by almost 60 percent for new rentals since 2009.
